Exploratory Analysis of NHS Service Utilisation, Missed Appointments, and Social Media Insights¶

🗂️ Project Overview¶

This project explores patterns in service utilisation, missed appointments and turnaround times across the NHS network. The goal is to inform budgeting and infrastructure planning decisions by visualiusing usage, inefficiencies and public sentiment. We will also evaluate whether external data sources such as Twitter can provide actionable insights.

Analyse patterns and trends in NHS service utilisation to inform effective resource allocation and budgeting decisions.

Has there been adequate staffing and capacity in the networks?

What was the actual utilisation of resources?

Key focus areas:

  • What are the trends in service utilisation over time?
  • Are missed appointments increasing or decreasing, and is this over a particular period?
  • Do platforms such as Twitter (X) correlate with system-wide pressure points?

📊 NHS Service Utilisation Patterns¶

  • Trends in context type and national category over time
  • Comparison of number of appointment volume vs staffing capacity
  • Analysis of booking-to-appointment turnaround time
  • Evaluation of improved mapping for appointments

⛔ Missed Appointments¶

  • Frequency and rate of missed appointments
  • Temporal patterns: seasonality and commonly missed appointment types
  • Investigation of whether longer turnaround times correlate with higher missed appointments

💬 Social Media Sentiment Analysis (Twitter)¶

  • Trends in tweet volume and sentiment over time
  • Spikes during notable NHS-related events such as COVID-19
  • Exploration of correlations between sentiment, missed appointments, and turnaround times

📊 Data Overview¶

This project uses both internal NHS datasets and external social media data from Twitter to analyse service usage and public sentiment.

🔵 Internal NHS Data¶

  • actual_duration.csv:
    • Appointment dates
    • Duration of each appointment
    • Number of appointments

📌 Useful for analysing appointment length and capacity trends by location

  • appointments_regional.csv:
    • Appointment dates
    • Attendance status (attended, DNA, unknown)
    • Appointment mode (Face-to-Face, Home Visit, Telephone, Unknown, Video/Online)
    • Days between booking and appointment
    • Count of appointments

📌 Enables analysis of appointment delivery methods and turnaround times.

  • national_category.xlsx:
    • Appointment dates
    • Service setting (GP, PCN etc)
    • Context type (clinical purpose)
    • National category (defined reasoning for appointment)
    • Count of appointments

📌 Provides understanding of appointment purposes and how they may change over time.

🟠 External NHS Data¶

  • tweets.csv:
    • Full tweet texts
    • Number of favourites and retweets

📌 Utilised to gauge public sentiment and engagement with healthcare topics.

The internal data provides operational insights, while external data offers context through public sentiment.

❓ Which service setting was the most popular for NHS North West London from 1 January to 1 June 2022?¶

In [27]:
# Create a variable presenting only rows with 'W2U3Z' in its 'sub_icb_location_name
nc_subset = nc[nc['sub_icb_location_name'].str.contains('W2U3Z', na = False)]

# Ensure 'appointment_date is datetime format
nc_subset['appointment_date'] = pd.to_datetime(nc_subset['appointment_date'], errors = 'coerce')

# Filter by date range: 1 Jan 2022 to 1 Jun 2022
start_date = '2022-01-01'
end_date = '2022-06-01'
nc_subset = nc_subset[
    (nc_subset['appointment_date'] >= start_date) & 
    (nc_subset['appointment_date'] <= end_date)
]

# Count appointments by service setting
service_counts = (
    nc_subset.groupby('service_setting')['count_of_appointments']
    .sum()
    .sort_values(ascending = False)
)

# View the output.
print("Total appointments by service setting (descending):")
print(service_counts)

# Write a sentence showing the most common service.
most_common_service = service_counts.idxmax()
most_common_count = service_counts.max()
print(f"\nThe service setting with the most appointments is: {most_common_service} ({most_common_count} appointments)")

# Group by year and month, then sum the appointment counts

📊 Visualisation of NHS Data¶

This section presents a series of visual analyses aimed at identifying patterns, trends and insights from the cleaned internal NHS data.

This includes interpreting of data, support hypotheses, and identify areas of interest for further investigation.

🧰 Import the necessary libraries for visualisations¶

In [32]:
# Import the necessary libraries.
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Set figure size.
sns.set(rc={'figure.figsize':(15, 12)})

# Set the plot style as white.
sns.set_style('white')

Change the data type of appointment month to string for ease of visualisation

In [33]:
# Change the data type of the appointment month to string to allow for easier plotting.
nc['appointment_month'] = nc['appointment_month'].astype(str)

📈 Monthly Appointments by Service Setting¶

In [34]:
# Aggregate the DataFrame to group the monthly appointments and service settings 
nc_ss = (
    nc.groupby(['appointment_month','service_setting'])['count_of_appointments']
    .sum()
    .reset_index()
    .sort_values(by = 'appointment_month')
)

# Use the nc_ss DataFrame to create a lineplot
sns.lineplot(
    data = nc_ss,
    x = 'appointment_month',
    y = 'count_of_appointments',
    hue = 'service_setting',
    marker = 'o'
)

# Format and label the graph
plt.xticks(rotation = 45)
plt.title('Monthly Appointments by Service Setting')
plt.xlabel('Month')
plt.ylabel('Number of Appointments')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# Create variables for 'retweet_count' and 'favorite_count'
retweet_counts = td['tweet_retweet_count'].value_counts().sort_index()
favorite_counts = td['tweet_favorite_count'].value_counts().sort_index()

# Limit to a reasonable count range
max_count = 10

# Reindex to ensure all counts from 0 to max_count are present
index = range(0, max_count + 1)
retweet_counts = retweet_counts.reindex(index, fill_value = 0)
favorite_counts = favorite_counts.reindex(index, fill_value = 0)

    'Retweets': retweet_counts,
    'Favourites': favorite_counts
}, index = index)

Is filtering by engagement thresholds valuable?

The vast majority of tweets received no engagement (526 had 0 retweets; 1027 had 0 favourites). Engagement drops off sharply as counts increase, only a small number of tweets achieved more than a handful of retweets or faavourites.

The distribution suggests that most healthcare-related tweets did not capture significant public attention. The small subset of tweets which did receive public attention may be valuable for further analysis.

Filtering tweets based on engagement thresholds (>= 5 retweets/favourites) can indicate patterns in more widely circulated content. In addition, zero engagement tweets may alo be spam or bots, which negatively impacts qualitative analysis. However, filtering out tweets based on engagement may result in a loss of overall context as engagement does not necessarily equate to importance.

# Loop through the messages, and create a list of values containing the # symbol.
tags = []

for y in [x.split(' ') for x in td['tweet_full_text'].dropna().values]:
    for z in y:
        if '#' in z:
            match = re.search(r'#\w+', z.lower())
            if match:
                tags.append(match.group())
           

tags = pd.Series(tags).value_counts()

Number Of Appointments

- Fluctuates, but there are periods of high appointment numbers during the winter season, likely caused by seasonal flu.

Utilisation

- Utilisation remains between 60-85% throughout indicating operation near max capacity.
- Utilisation is frequently around the 80% mark.

Relationship between Number of Appointments and Utilisation

- Increased demand directly translates to higher pressure on existing resources.
- Even during periods of fewer appointments (Apr 2022), utilisation remains relatively high (> 60%)

Should the NHS increase staff levels? - Yes

- Sustained high utilisation means:
    * Risk of burnout and compromised care - Negatively impact a patient's safety.
    * Lack of resilience - little room to handle unexpected events, staff absences or surges in demand.

- Improving staffing leads to:
    * Reduced wait times
    * Improved staff well-being and retention.
    * Enhanced quality of care
    * Greater flexibility to manage fluctuating demand.

Data Limitations

- There is no staff capacity reference so we are limited to conclusively determine if the NHS requires more staff.

📌 The NHS should start planning to allocate more staff in areas where utilisation is particularly high.

There is not a dramatic shift in the proportion or difference between Face-to-Face and Telephone appointments.

Face to Face leads several million appointments over Telephone calls.

By observing the peaks in the two most common appointment modes (Face-to-Face and Telephone), the months with the highest overall appointments are:

  • October 2021
  • November 2021
  • March 2022

🔍 Summary of Findings and Recommendations¶

🧠 Key Findings:¶

- Staff utilisation peaked above 80% during key months.
- GPs handled most appointments, with limited delegation to other staff
- Wait times for appointments showed a majority of the same day or between 2 and 7 days, with a noticeable amount exceeding 7 days.
- Service settings data showed a considerable number of records unmapped.
- #ai, #job, #digitalhealth were the most popular hashtags recorded.

✅ Recommendations:¶

- Increase staffing during high-demand months by increasing base level or employing temporary staff during surges.
- Shift appropriate tasks to nurses and support staff to reduce strain on GPs.
- Improve appointment scheduling to reduce appointment turnovers of more than 7 days.
- Monitor utilisation metrics monthly to assess the demand on NHS services. 
- Popular hashtags reflect public interest in NHS job opportunities, and the growing role of digital health which could help relieve pressure on NHS services, by decreasing the need for certain appointments.

⚠️ Data Limitations:¶

- Twitter data does not contain the dates of tweets which makes it harder to pinpoint when they were most popular.
- We do not know staffing numbers within the networks which makes minimum staffing numbers harder to match with current utilisation - thus making it difficult to determine if there has been adequate staff in the networks.

Has there been adequate staffing and capacity in the networks?

Staff utilisation regularly exceeded 80% during peak months, indicating the sytem was operating close to full capacity. This suggests staffing levels may not have been sufficient enough to handle demand without strain. However, due to the absence of staffing headcount data, we cannot confirm if there was adequacy across the networks.

What was the actual utilisation of resources?

GPs delivered majority of the appointments, while nurses and other staff were under-utilised in comaprison. The utilisation of other healthcare professionals grew, however the majority of appointments are still performed by GPs. Wait time data shows signs of a capacity strain, as a noticeable number of appointments exceeded 7 days.
